observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. Direct the Supply/Property Officer to:
a. Revisit the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
b. Coordinate with all offices and prepare an updated list of all PPE items as well as the PPE’s Property Cards and costing ₱50,000.00 and above for each office using “Annex A” of the aforementioned Circular;
c. Prepare the Inventory and Inspection Reports of Unserviceable Properties for all obsolete and unserviceable properties;
d. Verify if the PPE items were already disposed with supporting IIRUP or transferred/donated to other government agencies with the supporting PTR and submit the same to the Accounting Unit;
e. Inform the Head of the Agency of the non-existing/missing PPEs without pending Request for Relief; and
f. Prepare/update all Property Cards of all PPE items.
b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Revisit the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
b. Update/prepare PPELCs for all PPE items per category in the Accounting records;
c. Ensure that updated PPELCs reconcile with the controlling PPE General Ledger accounts;
d. Take up the necessary accounting entries to recognize PPEs found at the station, PPEs lost, and the corresponding receivables from concerned accountable officers/personnel; and
e. Collaborate with the Property Unit and determine the person/s accountable for the non-existing/missing PPEs not otherwise disposed of transferred.
c. Direct the Property Unit and the Accounting Unit to henceforth reconcile based on complete physical inventory count of all PPEs.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. Direct the Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer to:
a. Revisit the provisions of COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 22, 2022;
b. Collaborate and cause the immediate reconciliation of PPE records, reports, and balances;
c. Upon reconciliation of PPE, identify the items that are below the ₱50,000.00 capitalization threshold and cause the immediate reclassification to Semi-Expendable Property thereof;
d. Take appropriate actions as provided for in COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 22, 2022 such as, but not limited to: 1) Creation of Semi-Expendable Property Cards and Ledger Cards, 2) Preparation of Inventory Custodian Slips, and 3) Updating of Property Acknowledgement Receipts for those issued items.
e. Prepare a Registry of Semi-Expendable Property Issued (RegSPI)
f. Inform the Head of the Agency of the non-existing/missing PPEs without pending Request for Relief;
g. Henceforth comply with the provision of COA Circular No. 2022-004.
b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Effect necessary adjustments in the financial records and reports reconciled items based on the reconciliation with the Supply Officer.
b. Reflect the restated balances in the next financial reporting period with corresponding disclosures in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the concerned Municipal Officials to:
a. Rehabilitation of Stage-Jagnaya:
   a. Complete the plastering as programmed in the POW;
   b. Install the roofing of ₱55,820.00 as programmed in the POW
   c. Const. of Brgy Health Station, Agbun-od
      a. Immediately return the two office tables and five computer chairs for ₱32,500.00 to the barangay health station;
      b. Replace the decayed ceiling boards and require repair on the roofing, if necessary;
      c. Require replacement of the door panels from the supplier;
d. Establishment of Public Cemetery, Phase III at Brgy. Pangabuan
   a. Construct the Entrance Gate of ₱106,417.75 per Program of Work;
e. Multi-Purpose Vehicle
   a. Submit the Property Acknowledgement Receipt for the issued vehicle, to ascertain the official accountable for its safekeeping;
   b. Justify why the vehicle was left in its current state and no action/report was undertaken for its proper repair;
f. Unaccounted Materials and Labor Cost
   a. Direct the Municipal Accountant to verify the actual related charges, payment, if any, and accumulated cost of the implemented nine PPAs for infrastructure assets or buildings still with an on-going construction status;
   b. Direct the Project Engineer in charge to submit written justification on the causes of why projects are implemented without a recorded cost, either on materials or labor for ongoing/completed projects implemented by administration.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. Constitute a Disposal Committee comprised of a Chairperson and Members and a Secretariat pursuant to COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024;
b. Direct the Disposal Committee and the Secretariat to comply with the undertakings stated in 2.2 of the same COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 and cause the timely proceedings of the disposal;
c. Submit a duly accomplished Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) with appraisal values and mode of disposal indicated therein, Waste Materials Report (WMR), and Property Transfer Report, if applicable, to the Auditor concerned for proper endorsement to the COA Technical Services Office (TSO);
d. Direct Supply/Property Officer and the Disposal Committee to furnish the Municipal Accountant copies of the documents of the duly approved and concluded disposal activities; and
e. Direct the Accountant to make the necessary entries/adjustments to record the dropping from the Books of Accounts the disposed properties and ensure that proceeds from the sale, if any, are remitted to the Bureau of the Treasury.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. Direct the end-users to formulate their respective PPMPs for different PPAs, particularly infrastructure projects, during the budget preparation and submit to the Budget Officer for review, in forms and content as provided in Section 7.3.2 of the IRR of RA 9184;
b. Direct the BAC and the BAC Secretariat to: a) Consolidate all reviewed PPMPs, particularly the procurement of construction materials, in the APP in the form and content as provided in Section 7.3.4 of the IRR of RA 9184; and 2) Post the NOA, PO/ CA, and NTP in the PhilGEPS and the website of the Procuring Entity within the prescribed period as provided in Sections 37.1.6 and 37.4.2, of the IRR of RA 9184;
c. For procurement through the alternative mode of procurement: c) Post the RFQs in the PhilGEPS website, the website of the procuring entity, if available, and at any conspicuous place of the premises of the municipality; and d) Require the suppliers to submit the documents required in Appendix A of Annex H, of the IRR of RA 9184, namely, Mayor’s Permit, PhilGEPs Registration, Income/Business Tax Return, and Omnibus Sworn Statement.

