We recommended and Management agreed to require: 

The Inventory Committee to revise the   RPCPPE as of the end of CY 2022 to include the 12 Brand New FB Scrum-Patient Transport Vehicles (MultiCabs)   acquired in CYs 2021 and 2022.

b.	Revise the Certificate of Turnover to include the following:

b.1 The recipient is accountable for the Brand New FB Scrum-Patient Transport Vehicle (MultiCabs) turned over to the Barangay and be immediately accountable to the officer issuing said vehicle;

b.2 Identify the person responsible/accountable and has actual physical possession of government property or entrusted with its custody and control is responsible for its proper use and care and to exercise due diligence in the utilization and safekeeping thereof;

b.3  The recipient reports regularly to the municipal government to apprise the status (physical condition, legal obligations, record of travel during the reporting period with supporting trip tickets) and other relevant information related to the vehicle;

b.4 The municipal government regularly inspects the Rescue Vehicle assigned to the recipient, prepares, and submits a report on the Status of the Rescue Vehicle to the Municipal Mayor;

b.5 The municipal government marks the vehicle with "FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY" on the two side doors of the Vehicle with the official seal of the municipal government.

b.6 The recipient barangay to provide a garage for the vehicle to ensure security and protection.

b.7 The Rescue Vehicle will be used solely for emergency and rescue operations The details of the vehicles are detailed in Annex I where the Certificate of Registration and Official Receipt, Plate Number, Chassis Number, Engine Number, vehicle type, and location are indicated. 

c. The Property Officer to provide the Audit Team LTO-issued Certificate of Registration and Official Receipt   of the fourth vehicle as listed in Annex I;

d.	The Property Officer to conduct an inventory of the turned-over vehicles to 12 barangay recipients to ascertain their existence, exact location, and operational status;

e.	The Property Officer to furnish the Audit Team with certified copies of Certificates of Turnover for reference in audit;

f.	Submit the DILG approval/authority to acquire the vehicles pursuant to Item 5.1.3  of, the Revised Guidelines on Motor Vehicle Acquisition by Local Government Units.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the:

a) MSWDO to:

Justify the inclusion of non-residents in the List of Affected Families by Typhoon Odette;

Enhance verification and validation procedures for household and individuals affected by any calamities;

b) Municipal Accountant to:

Properly monitor the disbursements of Financial Assistance when there are deviations from the source documents (e.g. identification, proof of residency, etc).

We recommended and Management agreed to:

a. 	Require the focal person and implementing department to justify the non-implementation of eight PPAs totaling ₱5.699 million;

b. 	Enhance monitoring activities on the implementation of PPAs funded by the National Government; and

c. 	Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct regular verification and reconciliation of unexpended balances of fund transfer and return/remit balances to source agency;

We recommended and Management agreed to:

a. 	Require the Human Resource Officer to review the staffing requirements of each department and recommend the hiring of qualified personnel for a regular appointment, if necessary, to regulate the employment of personnel under Job Order Contract; 

b. 	Hire only JO personnel in accordance with the necessity and urgency of the department’s needs;

c. 	Assess the individual assignments of all job order personnel to avoid redundant and duplicating work accomplishments; and

d. 	Henceforth, strictly comply with Section 76 of RA No. 7160.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Require the SWM Board to:

Strengthen the 10-year SWM Plan through the formulation of the current year’s SWM Program containing all SWM PPAs, from waste reduction at source, collection, recycling, storage, processing, disposal, and other related SWM activities pursuant to Rule VI, Section 4(b) of the IRR of RA 9003;

Appropriate funds for the current year’s SWM PPA which shall be assigned in the MENRO for their effective and efficient implementation;

Direct the MENRO Office to regularly supervise, monitor, and evaluate the implementation of all SWM activities; and

Provide the necessary funding and a suitable site for the Sanitary Landfill, if warranted;

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Strictly comply with provisions of COA Circular 77-61 and ensure that all disbursements for fuel consumption (gasoline and oil) of government vehicles are duly supported by properly accomplished and approved serially Driver’s Trip Tickets (Appendix A, Annex B);

Require the concerned drivers to prepare the Monthly Report of Official Travels (Appendix F, Annex C) as well as the designated agency personnel to prepare Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption (Appendix G, Annex D) and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to book up as Fuel, Oil, and Lubricants Expense only those that are duly supported by the Monthly Report of Official Travels, Report of Fuel Consumption, with a duly filled-up Driver’s Trip Tickets.

